<article xml:id="markovtree"> 
<title>Markov Chains on a Tree</title>

<frontmatter>

<titlepage>
 <author>
                    <personname>Kenneth Levasseur</personname>
                    <department>Department of Mathematics and Statistics</department>
                    <institution>
                        <line>University of Massachusetts Lowell</line>
                        <line>Lowell, Massachusetts, USA</line>
                    </institution>
                    <email>kenneth_levasseur@uml.edu</email>
                </author>
<date><today /></date>

 </titlepage>

<abstract> <p> The Stochastic Abacus can employed to used to compute absorbing probabilities for a Markov Chain on a tree.  For all but the simplest cases, the abacus can't really be implemented due to the large number of steps needed for completion.  In this paper, a technique for anticipating the outcome is introduced.</p> </abstract>

</frontmatter>

<introduction><title>Introduction</title>
<p>In the 1970's, Engel <xref ref="biblio-engel"/> devised the Stochastic Abacus as a way to compute probabilities for certain discrete probability problems with minimal numerical computation.   The Stochastic Abacus has found more widespread exposure due to a recent article by Propp <xref ref="biblio-propp"/> in Math Horizons. In Levasseur <xref ref="biblio-levasseur"/>  the game of <q>Pass the Buck</q> was analyzed on a tree, with a recursive construction that efficiently produced the winning probabilities. In this note, we use similar logic to describe how absorbing probabilities on a finite Markov chain with rational transition $probs can be derived with a generalization of the method used in <xref ref="biblio-levasseur"/>. One such example is the playing of a tennis game that has reached Deuce. 
</p>

 <figure xml:id="fig-tennis-1">
		 <caption>Tennis at Deuce as a Markov Chain
		 </caption>
		 <image width="60%" source="images/fig-tennis-1.png">
			  <description></description>
		 </image>
</figure>


 </introduction>

<section xml:id="section-scope"> <title>Scope and Notation</title> 
<p>The class of Markov chains consider here are ones for which the transition graph is a tree, transition probabilities are all rational and two or more more of the states of the process are connected to absorbing states.  Given a starting state, we compute the absorbing probabilities for the process.</p>
<p>For each state in the Markov chain under consideration, we assume that the probabilities are rational.  The sum of transition $probs out of that state add up to one. If they are all represented as fractions with a common denominator we construct an <q>abacus graph</q> with edges weighted by the numerators of these fractions.  The out-degree of the state will then be the denominator of the fractions.</p>
<p>For each state <m>k</m>,  
	<ul>
	<li><p><m>t_{k,i}</m> is the edge weight of the edge <m>(k,i)</m>, and </p></li>
 	<li><p><m>a_k</m> is the edge weight of the edge connecting <m>k</m> to its absorbing state.</p></li>
 	</ul>
 	</p>
</section> 

<section xml:id="section-stochastic-abacus"> <title>The Stochastic Abacus</title>

<p>Engle's Stochastic Abacus is a chip firing algorithm that, when complete, allows computation of absorbing probabilities in a Markov Chain. Chip firing algorithms take place on a directed graph with vertices that contain variable numbers of chips (or coins or M &amp; M's). The chips move around by the process of chip firing.  This can happen if a vertex contains enough chips to distribute along all of it's outgoing edges according to their weights. What makes the algorithm work is that these firings mimic random events. If a vertex for a transition state has at least as many chips as its weighted out-degree, distributing them to each neighbor according to the edge weights captures all possible outcomes when the is in that state.  In the course of the whole stochatic abacus algorithm, the number of firings at any vertex/state is proportional to the number of times we expect that vertex/state to have have been visited before reaching an absorbing state.  </p>

<p> We will illustrate how the algorthm is set up and executed for a game of tennis.  When a tennis game has reached a point where both players have won three points, the game continues until one of the players is ahead by two points. There are five states in the process/game at this point. The terminology used in tennis for the states follows.  In any game, one of the players hits the ball first and is referred to as the server, and the other player is the receiver.  </p>
<dl>
           <li>
             <title>Deuce</title>
             <p>
               The transient state in which two players are tied with at least three points each.
             </p>
           </li>
           <li>
             <title>Ad-In</title>
             <p>
               The transient state where the server is ahead by one point, having won a point while the game is in Deuce.
             </p>
           </li>
           <li>
             <title>Ad-Out</title>
             <p>
            The transient state where the receiver is ahead by one point, having won a point while the game is in Deuce.
             </p>
           </li>
           <li>
             <title>Hold</title>
             <p>
               The absorbing state where the server is ahead by two points and the game is over.  
             </p>
           </li>
           <li>
             <title>Break</title>
             <p>
               The absorbing state where the receiver is ahead by two points and the game is over.
             </p>
           </li>
         </dl>
<p>Strictly speaking, a real tennis game isn't a Markov chain because players' memories of previous points could affect their play, but the Markov chain assumption is a reasonable approximation of reality.  In what follows, we will assume that for any point, the probability that the server wins the point is 2/3.  We can visualize the process with a transition graph, <xref ref="fig-tennis-1"  text="type-global"/>, where the labels on each edge indicate the probability of movement to the terminal vertex from the initial vertex of the edge.
</p>
		<figure xml:id="fig-tennis">
			 <caption>The transition graph for a tennis game that reaches Deuce.</caption>
			 <image width="60%" source="images/fig-tennis-1.png">
				  <description><p>A graph with five vertices, one for each possible state on a tennis game that has reached Deuce.</p></description>
			 </image>
		</figure>

<p>We might wonder as to the likelihood that the server wins a game under these assumptions if the game has reached the Deuce state.  
</p>

<p>The abacus for tennis at duece is constructed by first converting the graph on which it is played from an undirected graph to a directed graph, where each undirected edge is replace with a pair of directed edges, one in each direction. The vertices of the original graph are referred to as the  <q>internal vertices.</q>  Then we add <q>absorbing vertices</q> to the graph, one for each internal vertex, and an edge leading into each absorbing vertex from its corresponding internal vertex, as in <xref ref="fig-tennis-2"  text="type-global"/>. For this example we use the notation <m>v_x</m> for an internal vertex and <m>t_x</m> for its corresponding absorbing vertex.  The absorbing vertex attached to its internal vertex are so called because they capture (or absorb) chips in the process of chip firing that we discuss below. </p> 

 <figure xml:id="fig-tennis-2">
		 <caption>Stochatic Abacus for Tennis at Deuce
		 </caption>
		 <image width="60%" source="images/fig-tennis-2.png">
			  <description>A graph with five vertices, one for each possible state on a tennis game that has reached Deuce.</description>
		 </image>
</figure>

<p>Now that we have the graph for the abacus constructed, we distribute chips to each internal vertex.  These internal vertices, which correspond to the vertices of the original game graph, each get as many chips as one less than the outdegree of the vertex in the abacus. In <xref ref="fig-tennis-2"  text="type-global"/>, the number of chips each vertex is given is indicated inside the vertex.  Initially, the absorbing vertices get no chips.  The starting location of the <q>buck</q> in Pass the Buck  is the starting vertex of the algorithm. In all of our examples, the starting vertex is the root of the tree.  At this point in the algorithm,  we say that the system is <q>critically loaded.</q> The algorithm then consists of repeatedly adding a chip to the start vertex and then <q>firing</q> chips as long as the number of chips in any internal vertex is greater than or equal to the outdegree of that vertex. Firing at a vertex involves distributing a chip along each outgoing edge of the <q>loaded vertex</q> to neighboring vertices, including it's own absorbing vertex.   When no more firing can take place we examine the contents of the internal vertices.  If the chip counts in all internal vertices match the critical loading condition, we end the algorithm. Otherwise repeat the process, adding a single chip to the starting vertex.</p>
 

<p>After we have returned to the original critical loading of internal vertices, the probability that the process ends in any particular absorbing state is equal to the number of chips in its  absorbing vertex divided by the total number of chips in all absorbing vertices. The way to see why this is plausible is to consider that the process of firing chips at a vertex simultaneously  simulates all the possibilities in the game weighted by the transition probabilities. Moving a chip to the absorbing vertex captures the situation where absorbtion takes place at that state, while the chips that move to adjacent transition states capture the situations where the process moves on that state.  See Snell <xref ref="biblio-snell"/> for a complete proof. </p>
<p> Here is a step by step account of how the process plays out in our example, with the numbers in each vertex's column being the number of chips it holds. </p>

<table>
  <title>Steps in performing the stochatic abacus a tennis game at Deuce.</title>
  <tabular halign="center">
    <row header="yes" bottom="minor" >
      <cell>Step </cell>
      <cell>Comment</cell>
      <cell>Ad-In</cell>
      <cell>Deuce</cell>
      <cell>Ad-Out</cell>
      <cell>Hold</cell>
      <cell>Break</cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell>1</cell>
      <cell>Critically loaded</cell>
      <cell>2</cell>
      <cell>2</cell>
      <cell>2</cell>
      <cell>0</cell>
      <cell>0</cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell>2</cell>
      <cell>Add 1 chip to Deuce</cell>
      <cell>2</cell>
      <cell>3</cell>
      <cell>2</cell>
      <cell>0</cell>
      <cell>0</cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell>3</cell>
      <cell>Deuce fires</cell>
      <cell>4</cell>
      <cell>0</cell>
      <cell>3</cell>
      <cell>0</cell>
      <cell>0</cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell>4a</cell>
      <cell>Ad-In fires</cell>
      <cell>1</cell>
      <cell>1</cell>
      <cell>3</cell>
      <cell>2</cell>
      <cell>0</cell>
   </row>
    <row>
      <cell>4b</cell>
      <cell>Ad-Out fires</cell>
      <cell>1</cell>
      <cell>3</cell>
      <cell>0</cell>
      <cell>2</cell>
      <cell>1</cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell>5</cell>
      <cell>Deuce fires</cell>
      <cell>3</cell>
      <cell>0</cell>
      <cell>1</cell>
      <cell>2</cell>
      <cell>1</cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell>6</cell>
      <cell>Ad-In fires</cell>
      <cell>0</cell>
      <cell>1</cell>
      <cell>0</cell>
      <cell>4</cell>
      <cell>1</cell>
    </row>
    <row>
